metadata.name: Mixed Signals #54
metadata.description:
Mixed Signals is a series of 128 generative animated loops. Each animation is constructed with a grid of curves that creates illusions of waveforms marching across the screen or shapes bubbling in and out of existence. Some rare mints are possible, since features are available in the following categories:

extremely low, very low, low, medium, high, very high, extremely high

where medium is the most common, low and high are rarer, very low and very high are even rarer, etc.

Interactions:
Ctrl+S / Cmd+S: Save a 2048 x 2048 screen capture
Ctrl+Shift+S / Cmd+Shift+S (Press, don't hold): Export image sequence of 3 second loop 
Space bar: Pause/Unpause the animation

Original artwork by Stephen Jue ¬∑ Made with canvas-sketch ¬∑ 2022

metadata.name: White flags #160
metadata.description:
All I can do for the moment, is give the world some paint-bombs and color explosions. Focus on things you like and love, don't let the hate consume you.


mouse-click: 
- screen scaled image
- full image 3000x3000

The scaled image will reset after some time, with a new drawing
I like it, when you make a work, that will refresh after sometime,
chill out, and see it go.

Tech - Vanilla java-script; a custom build 'soft' 3D-engine.
I can do more things if I can control the (3D) drawing, the color of every pixel.
Also added a z-buffer to the  line-drawing routine this time.
More information in the source-code.

metadata.name: rive #276
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns‚Äìand the comfort we find in them‚Äìin slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

rive
abstractment, 2022

___________________________

metadata.name: Square Dots #51
metadata.description:
I wanted to make something that resembles my screenprinting years. Especially when I experimented with different substrates and inks; tried to understand the mechanism.
I always liked organised chaos, when the objects, shapes or colours do not really match individually, but if you throw them together, it generates some rhythm. 
The best part of printing by hand is the ability to make errors. These mistakes lead to something unique, something fun. 
This is my version of SCREEN printing.

Press the "s" key in live view to save a 6000x6000 pixel image.

2.5% of the royalties go to the Processing Foundation, and 2.5% go to the minters.

metadata.name: one hour #87
metadata.description:
`one hour` is an interactive installation exploring the bond between humans and computers, inviting you to pause and share a meditative moment with an algorithmic stranger.

Rather than conventionally interacting with the piece, lower your guard and allow it to interact with you through an intimately human connection - a heart beat. `one hour` follows this heart as it beats through an hour of its enduring existence, captured by an EKG divided into 60 rows of 60 seconds each. Stylistically, it emulates realistic paper and ink using custom texture and line renderers. The piece will play through the duration of the hour, pause for five minutes, then begin anew.

`one hour` was created for a physical installation, projected to a wall and animated in real time. By default it will render at high speed to reveal the preview. For the most immersive experience at home, it should be viewed in full screen and adjusted to real time speed (controlled via the number keys).

||| controls

[s] save as png
[r] reset animation
[l] toggle looping [default on]
[1-5] adjust render speed
[--1] real time (1 hour) [recommended]
[--2] 6x (10 minutes)
[--3] 60x (1 minute)
[--4] 300x (12 seconds) [default]
[--5] full speed

metadata.name: Swatches #11
metadata.description:
Swatches is the first generative token project by Paul Drzal.

Like photography gels scattered on the light table, the layers combine to create the composition.  A random four-color palette in varying opacities creates your swatch, hand pulled on the screen.

Colors are inspired by the bold stylized drawings of architects Wes Jones and Neil Denari.

Press ‚Äòs‚Äô to save your Swatch.  Zoom out and refresh to save a larger file.

metadata.name: Nounfall #345
metadata.description:
Nounfall is drawn exclusively from the 234 heads and 21 glasses that are used to build the current Nouns collection. The background colors are all pulled from the blessed Noun palette.

This is ok because Nouns are CC0, which basically means public domain. Check out nouns.wtf for more info.

They make for fun social media banners when cropped, if you wanna show off you fandom of Nouns.

C : Clear screen and start animation over
S : Save current image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density to the respective number

So, if you want a high resolution file, tap `6` for it to redraw, and then `S` to save. You can also save while it's animating if you like, which is fun too.

metadata.name: Snow Mountains #1
metadata.description:
"Snow Mountains"

Since my first trek in India in 2013 (Stok Kangri - 6137m), I have always been fascinated by these gigantic boulders.

They remind us how small we are facing nature.

With this collection (created with p5js), I have given them back their power.

Here are the variables used:
- Each point is calculated randomly creating random shapes
- A mountain chosen randomly among the 425 highest.
- A color palette chosen randomly from the 100 proposed.

By clicking on the image, you can save it in .jpeg format.

These mountains will enhance your NFT collection.

metadata.name: Stepping Stones #567
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

---------------

metadata.name: Fluid Edge #111
metadata.description:
~~ FLUID EDGE ~~

Press [s] to save a png at the current resolution.

Press [x] to save a svg at the current resolution.

Press [2/4/6/8/0] to change resolution to 2/4/6/8/10K along the shortest edge.

Press [l] to initiate download of 400 png frames at current resolution. Can be assembled into a perfectly looping video / GIF.

Press [space] to pause/unpause animation.

This work uses p5.js and p5.svg.js libraries.
